We miss you and are so excited to welcome you back to school this fall! We are planning for a school year of learning together in an in-person classroom environment. However, we realize things can change between now and the first day of school. Take a moment to watch this video to hear more about how we’re preparing for the 2020-21 school year. We created detailed plans around four learning scenarios. These plans are in-line with our state's department of education plan, which outlines required and recommended safety protocols for the 2020-21 school year based on the status of coronavirus in our community.
For the most up to date information on back to school plan, please visit: https://www.nhaschools.com/en/COVID-19

post_text:
Dear Eagle Crest Families,

Now that the school year has come to an end, we would like to congratulate all of our students on their successful completion of the 2019-2020 school year. We would also like our students to know that we look forward to seeing them all some time soon!

Report Cards for the 2019-2020 school year are now available on Parent Portal. When you view them, you will see a 1st Trimester and 2nd Trimester Grade. For the 3rd Trimester you will see a P for participated or an NP for Not Participated. The final grade will be an average of the 1st and 2nd Trimester grades. If you can not access parent portal, or you need a report card printed, please contact the office.… More

post_text:
All students will be provided personal learning devices!

While we may not know exactly what the next school year holds—whether we’re back in school, remote, or a combination of both—we have a plan in place and the technology to support it. All of our students will be provided personal learning devices and will be able to attend online classes.

Taking all challenges in stride, our teachers and staff are doing everything in their power to finish the school year off as normally as possible. From virtual spirit weeks to online graduation ceremonies, we are focusing on creating solid memories for students who are advancing to high school next year. https://bit.ly/2zHnGoY

Every dance shared through the app results in a donation to the newly formed West Michigan Hero Fund. Our founder J.C. Huizenga has made a generous donation to support the fund. Additionally, our schools will be competing against each other for the greatest number of dances to win three cash prizes.

column1: Watch the kids enjoy hours of fun with their new sidewalk paint."
link:
Here is a great activity to make and then use outside to get some fresh air. Be sure to show us your photos if you try this activity at home.

Puffy Sidewalk Chalk Paint Ingredients
1 cup flour
1 cup water
1 tablespoon dish soap, any brand
5-10 drops food coloring or washable paint

How to Make Sidewalk Chalk Paint:
In a large mixing bowl stir together the flour and water until there are no lumps.
Stir in the dish soap to the flour mixture.
Add food coloring of your choice until you reach the desired color.
Pour the mixture into a squeeze bottle. (Try an old ketchup bottle or something similar that has been washed thoroughly if you don't have one.)
If you are making multiple colors, make each color in a separate bowl.
Watch the kids enjoy hours of fun with their new sidewalk paint.

Thursday, May 9, is a half day of school for Tulip Time. Students in Young Fives through 3rd grade will be dismissed at 11:10 AM and 4th through 8th grade will be dismissed at 11:20 AM. Please make arrangements to have your children picked up at the proper dismissal time.
The Tulip Time Kinderparade is Thursday afternoon. If your child is marching in the band or with the 1st-5th grade classes, they need to be at our meeting location by 1:30 p.m. Eagle Crest will be lining up on 10th St between Columbia Ave. and College Ave. Our pick up location at the end of the parade is 13th and Van Raalte. All students need to be picked up as soon as they finish marching. Happy Tulip Time!
